{
  "doc_id": "59681",
  "text": "Tumour-bearing animals can present changes in the activities of oxidant and antioxidant enzymes that influence the antioxidant capacity of skeletal muscle and may lead to oxidative stress [CITATION_1] . Previous studies have shown decreased catalase activity in the liver and kidneys of tumour-bearing rats [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In the plasma of cancer patients, there are also marked changes in the activities of antioxidant enzymes [CITATION_4] . These changes have been attributed to an increase in TNF-α that reduces hepatic catalase activity [CITATION_5] . Glutathione peroxidase and transferase are the major enzymes involved in protection against cells peroxidative damage [CITATION_6] . In addition to a possible control by hormones and cytokines, reactive oxygen species (ROS) may also regulate the activity of antioxidant enzymes [CITATION_7] . In the present study, WF, especially at high concentrations, was extremely cytotoxic, as shown by the decrease in NAC (which reflects a decrease in DNA content). Additionally, the reduced GST activity seen mainly after 48 h and 72 h of treatment indicated a loss of cellular protective mechanisms and increased in oxidative stress as expressed as malondialdehyde content 24 h after WF treatment, inducing a cumulative damage on myotubes. These results agree with those of Tang et al. [CITATION_8] , who demonstrated that metabolites of the lipoxygenase (12-LOX) pathway were involved in the survival of Walker cells by protecting against the increase in lipid peroxidation and the loss of glutathione-S-transferase activity.",
